The issue here is that the `MockMvc` configuration is not properly set up to handle exceptions. When an exception occurs in a controller, it's caught by the Spring framework and returned as a JSON response with a 500 status code (INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR).

To test how your custom exception handlers handle different types of exceptions, you can use the following approach:

```java
@Test
@DisplayName("General Exception 처리 테스트")
void handleGeneralExceptionTest() throws Exception {
    mockMvc.perform(get("/test-exceptions/general")
            .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
            .andExpect(status().isInternalServerError()) // This will pass because it's a default behavior of Spring

    // To test custom exception handling, you need to configure the MockMvc to throw an exception before calling perform()
    // You can use mockMvc.throwException() method for this
    when(mockMvc.throwException(any(Exception.class)))
            .thenReturn(new ResponseEntity<>(ErrorResponse.of(ResponseCode.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR), HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR));

    mockMvc.perform(get("/test-exceptions/general")
            .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
            .andDo(print())
            .andExpect(status().isInternalServerError()) // This should pass now because the custom exception handler is in effect
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.success").value(false))
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.code").value(ResponseCode.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR.getCode()))
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").value(ResponseCode.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR.getMessage()));
}
```

However, there's a better way to handle this situation using `MockMvc`'s `throwException()` method. This method allows you to specify the type of exception that should be thrown before calling `perform()`. Here's an example:

```java
@Test
@DisplayName("General Exception 처리 테스트")
void handleGeneralExceptionTest() throws Exception {
    when(mockMvc.throwException(any(Exception.class)))
            .thenThrow(new Exception("General exception for test"));

    mockMvc.perform(get("/test-exceptions/general")
            .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
            .andDo(print())
            .andExpect(status().isInternalServerError()) // This should pass now because the custom exception handler is in effect
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.success").value(false))
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.code").value(ResponseCode.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR.getCode()))
            .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").value(ResponseCode.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR.getMessage()));
}
```

This way, you can test your custom exception handling behavior with more accuracy. 

Remember to properly configure the `MockMvc` using `@AutoConfigureMockMvc` annotation and make sure that your controllers are annotated with `@RestController`.

